ce:section.ce:para:
Phthalocyanines (Pcs) are highly conjugated 18 – π macrocyclic compounds with interesting redox and electrocatalytic properties [1–3]. Phthalocyanines can be used as signal amplifiers as well as immobilization platforms for various biorecognition elements for the design of biosensors [4,5]. Two metallophthalocyanines (MPcs) are investigated as electrode modifiers towards biosensor design. The phthalocyanines are: a cobalt tetra-acetylphenoxy (CoTAcPhPc, Fig. 1
                     ) and a cobalt tris – (acetyl phenoxy)-mono-phenoxyacrylic acid phthalocyanine (CoMPhAaPc, Scheme 1
                     ). Cobalt was chosen as a central metal owing to the high catalytic activity of the CoPc derivatives [3,6]. It has been demonstrated that substituents on the periphery of the phthalocyanine ring strongly influence the solution redox chemistry of these materials [7–10]. The aim of this work is to investigate the effect of symmetry and substituent on the electrocatalytic properties of the above said phthalocyanines. The effect of replacing one acetylphenoxy ligand in the tetra substituted CoTAcPhPc, with a phenoxyacrylic acid ligand to form the CoMPhAaPc is investigated. The two complexes are compared as surface modifiers and signal amplifiers in the design of novel human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2) electrochemical biosensors. We have reported on the detection of HER2 in the presence of symmetrically substituted MPcs before [11,12]. This is the first time that an asymmetric phthalocyanine is employed for HER2 detection. The use of asymmetric Pcs is influenced by the fact that asymmetry is known to improve electrocatalytic activity of phthalocyanines and related porphyrins [13]. Acetophenone was chosen as the dominant substituent due to its rich electrochemistry [14]. In addition, acetophenone will allow for the formation of imine bond while the presence of acrylic acid allows for the formation of amide bond with the aptamer. Hence the activities of the Pcs will not only be determined by symmetry, but also by the type of bond. Acrylic acid derivatives are known for their electrocatalytic activity hence this substituent is employed in this work [15].

All electrochemical measurements were performed in 10 mM PBS of pH 7.4 containing 0.1 M KCl and 1 mM [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− at 100 mV/s, Fig. 4
                           A. The CV of ferricyanide was chosen as a marker to investigate the electron transfer properties of each modified surface. The electron transfer properties of the various surfaces were investigated by comparing the ΔEp values (anodic to cathodic peak potential separation). The ΔEp values (Table 1
                           ) for the designed sensors were 750 mV, 710 mV, 882 mV, 1180 mV and 1307 mV for the GCE/SNGQDs(1), GCE/SNGQDs(π)CoTAcPhPc(5), GCE/CoTAcPhPc(4), GCE/SNGQDs(π)CoMAcPhPc(3) and GCE/ CoMPhAaPc(2), respectively. The varying ΔEp obtained for the CoPcs in particular, can be attributed to the different substituents, symmetry and in turn their ability to mediate electron transfer on the GCE, Table 1. The symmetric CoTAcPhPc based GCE/CoTAcPhPc(4) and GCE/SNGQDs(π)CoTAcPhPc(5) had the lower ΔEp values compared to their asymmetric CoMPhAaPc based GCE/ CoMPhAaPc(2) and GCE/SNGQDs(π)CoMPhAaPc(3), counterparts. The conjugate based electrode showed better electron transfer properties compared to both the respective Pc based electrodes. This speaks to the SNGQDs, as highly π-conjugated nanomaterials and electrocatalysts on their own, and their ability to improve the electron transfer of the Pcs in the conjugate [26,27].
